    seniorNotes: "The senior framing is that multi-region is a business decision expressed as two numbers (RPO and RTO) and a budget, not a technology choice — you engineer backward from the tolerable data loss and downtime to the cheapest tier that hits them, rather than reaching for active-active because it sounds impressive. Two hard-won lessons: first, an untested DR plan has an effective RTO of infinity, so the drill IS the deliverable — schedule regional game days and treat a failed drill as a real incident. Second, active-active does not remove the CAP tradeoff, it forces you to confront it on every write; the pragmatic pattern most large systems land on is a single writer per data partition (home region) with global reads, which keeps writes conflict-free while still serving reads at the edge. Also keep an eye on the boring killers: DNS TTLs, a secret that only exists in one region, and inter-region egress cost, which can quietly dwarf your compute bill if you replicate carelessly.",
